\f2\cf3 [End of inserted reference material or article.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 27:23, 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 4\u8212?An angel told Paul that all those sailing with him would survive the storm\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scripture.] Acts 27:23, 24: This night an angel of the God to whom I belong and to whom I render sacred service stood by me and said: \u8216?Have no fear, Paul. You must stand before Caesar, and look! God has granted to you all those sailing with you.\u8217? [End of inserted scripture.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [End of inserted reference material or article.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 28:1, 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 \u8212?Paul was shipwrecked on Malta (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\i bt}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 -E 209 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 paragraph 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 8; 210 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 paragraph 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 1)\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scripture.] Acts 28:1, 2: After we made it to safety, we learned that the island was called Malta. And the foreign-speaking people showed us extraordinary kindness. They kindled a fire and received all of us kindly because of the rain that was falling and because of the cold. [End of inserted scripture.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li576 \par\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Inserted References\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\i bt}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 -E 209 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 paragraph 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 8\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 It turned out that the survivors were on the island of Malta, south of Sicily. (See the box \u8220?Malta\u8212?Where?\u8221?) The foreign-speaking people of the island showed them \u8220?extraordinary human kindness.\u8221? (Acts 28:2) They made a fire for these strangers who had reached their shore drenched and shivering. The fire helped them to get warm despite the cold and rain. It also gave rise to a miracle.\par}\par\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\i bt}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 -E 210 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 paragraph 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 1\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 The wealthy landowner Publius lived in the area. He may have been the leading Roman officer on Malta. Luke described him as \u8220?the principal man of the island,\u8221? employing the exact title that has been found on two Maltese inscriptions. He hospitably entertained Paul and his companions for three days. However, Publius\u8217? father was ill. Again Luke described a condition with accuracy. He wrote that the man \u8220?was lying down distressed with fever and dysentery,\u8221? citing the precise medical nature of the illness. Paul prayed and laid his hands on the man, and he was healed. Deeply impressed by this miracle, the local people brought other sick ones to be healed, and they brought gifts to fill the needs of Paul and his companions.\u8212?Acts 28:7-10.\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [End of inserted reference material or article.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 28:16, 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 7\u8212?Paul safely arrived in Rome (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\i w12 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 1/15 2:18)\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scripture.] Acts 28:16, 17: When finally we entered Rome, Paul was permitted to stay by himself with the soldier guarding him. However, three days later he called together the principal men of the Jews. When they had assembled, he said to them: \u8220?Men, brothers, although I had done nothing contrary to the people or the customs of our forefathers, I was handed over as a prisoner from Jerusalem into the hands of the Romans. [End of inserted scripture.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql \par\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Inserted Reference\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 Consider our last glimpse of Paul in the book of Acts, as recorded in Acts chapter\u160?28. Paul arrived in Rome, where he was to appear before Nero. He was kept in custody, perhaps chained to his guard. Yet, no chain could silence the zealous apostle! Paul continued to find ways to bear witness. (Read }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 28:17, 23, 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 4.) After three days, Paul summoned the principal men of the Jews in order to give them a witness. Then, on a chosen day, he gave an even greater witness. Verse\u160?23 states: \u8220?They [the local Jews] now arranged for a day with him, and they came in greater numbers to him in his lodging place. And he explained the matter to them by bearing thorough witness concerning the kingdom of God and by using persuasion with them concerning Jesus from both the law of Moses and the Prophets, from morning till evening.\u8221?\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [End of meeting part.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 \u8226? }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ab\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\b Digging for Spiritual Gems: }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 (8\u160?}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 minutes}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 )\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 Acts 2}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 8:30\u8212?What was Paul\u8217?s activity during and after his house arrest? (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\cf3 \u8220?he remained there for an entire two years\u8221? study note}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 , }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ai\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22\i nwtsty}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af0\afs22\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f3\fs22 -E)\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li660 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [Inserted scripture.] Acts 28:30: So he remained there for an entire two years in his own rented house, and he would kindly receive all those who came to him, [End of inserted scripture.]\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\li576 \par\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af2\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Inserted Reference\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql\fi-480\li480 {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 he remained there for an entire two years: During this two}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3  year }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 period, Paul wrote his letter to the Ephesians (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Ephesians 4}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 :1; 6:20), to the Philippians (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Philippians 1:7, 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 2-14), to the Colossians (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Colossians 4}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 :18), to Philemon (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Philemon 9}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 ), and apparently also to the Hebrews. His house arrest seems to have ended in about the year 61\u160?C.E. when he apparently was tried\u8212?perhaps before Emperor Nero or one of his representatives\u8212?and pronounced innocent. After his release, Paul characteristically remained active. It could have been during this period that he made his planned trip to Spain. (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Romans 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 5:28) According to Clement of Rome, who wrote in about the year 95\u160?C.E., Paul traveled \u8220?to the extreme limit of the W[est],\u8221? that is, of the Roman Empire. Paul\u8217?s three letters dated to the years after his release (1\u160?and 2\u160?Timothy and Titus) reveal that he apparently visited Crete, Macedonia, Nicopolis, and Troas. (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 1 Timothy 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 :3; }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 2 Timothy 4}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 :13; }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Titus 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 :5; 3:12) Some suggest that it was in Nicopolis, Greece, that Paul was again arrested and that he was back in prison in Rome in about the year 65\u160?C.E. This time, it seems that Nero showed no mercy. A fire had devastated Rome the year before, and according to Roman historian Tacitus, Nero falsely blamed the Christians. Nero then initiated a brutal campaign of persecution against them. When Paul wrote his second and final letter to Timothy, he expected to be executed soon, so he asked Timothy and Mark to come quickly. During this time, Luke and Onesiphorus showed great courage and risked their lives to visit Paul and comfort him. (}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 2 Timothy 1:16, 17; 4:6-9, 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 1) It was likely in about the year 65\u160?C.E. that Paul was executed. In both life and death, Paul was an outstanding witness to \u8220?all the things Jesus started to do and to teach.\u8221?\u8212?}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 Acts 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf5 :1.\par}\pard\plain\langnp1033\langfenp1033 \ltrpar\ql {\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf3 [End of inserted